benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/admin/queues - Get queues entries

covered: Valid Request: Multiple successful retrieval scenarios (no params, individual filters, combined filters) validate correct behavior for valid inputs.
Empty Response: Scenarios exist for no data and filters matching no entries (TC11, TC29).

Query Parameters: Extensive coverage for accountId, queueName, serviceName, minDate/maxDate, and flag parameters (withHistory, withInProcessing, withBusEvents, withNotifications) including combinations (TC02-TC10, TC23).
Error Scenarios / Validation: Invalid accountId format, account not found, malformed dates, and min/max date bounds are covered (TC13, TC14, TC25, TC24).
Security: Injection and XSS attempts in query parameters are included (TC17, TC26).
Resilience & Operational: Service unavailable, timeout, transient network recovery, and server error scenarios are present (TC16, TC19, TC27, TC30).
Performance / Scale: Large data volume and concurrent requests are considered (TC18, TC20).
Regression & Backward Compatibility: Regression for withHistory and backward-compatibility for omitted params are covered (TC21, TC22).
Content-Type: At least one scenario asserts application/octet-stream response (TC01).
Accessibility / Error messaging: API documentation and error payload consistency is included (TC28).
gaps: Pagination: No tests exercise pagination (limit/offset/page, paged responses, or pagination headers) for normal or large datasets.
Rate Limiting / Throttling: No tests verify API behavior under rate limits or returned 429 responses.
Caching Behavior: No scenarios check caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control), conditional requests, or cache invalidation.
Response Schema & Stream Validation: Tests assert "contains entries" but do not validate the octet-stream payload structure/format, item schema, or streaming/chunking behavior.
Content-Type / Consistency: Only TC01 asserts content type; other success scenarios do not validate that application/octet-stream is always used.
Boolean / Type Validation: No tests for invalid boolean or other malformed parameter types (e.g., withHistory=notabool).
Date-range edge cases: Missing test for invalid ranges like minDate > maxDate, and timezone/ISO format variations.
Authorization nuance: No test for forbidden (403) cases, expired tokens, or role-based access differences (e.g., non-admin authenticated user).
Rate/Load headers: No tests for headers that might be present for paging or rate-limit status (Retry-After, X-RateLimit-*)
Content negotiation / Accept header: No tests for behavior when Accept header differs or when the client expects JSON vs octet-stream.
recommendations: Add pagination tests: limit, offset/page tokens, expected pagination headers and behavior with large datasets; include boundary pages (first, last, empty page).
Add rate limiting tests: simulate many rapid requests to assert 429 responses and Retry-After header behavior, and validate graceful degradation.
Add caching tests: verify ETag and Cache-Control headers, conditional GETs (If-None-Match) and correct 304 responses where appropriate.
Validate response payload/schema: add tests that parse the octet-stream payload to validate record schema, ordering (if any), and that the streaming format is correct and consistent across responses.
Assert content-type consistently: include content-type checks in all success scenarios, not just the default case.
Add type/format negative tests: invalid boolean values, minDate > maxDate, unsupported date formats, and non-UUID accountId formats beyond the single invalid-case to cover variations.
Expand authorization tests: include expired tokens, insufficient-role (403) cases, and token-scoped access differences to ensure only admins can access this endpoint.
Add content negotiation tests: verify behavior when Accept header requests different media types and how the server responds (error vs negotiation).
Measure and assert performance for large-result sets together with pagination to avoid memory/timeout issues; include acceptable SLA thresholds and monitoring of response times.
